0.body: Welcome to Worldsmith Studio, a fully GUI-based builder for RPG's. This manual will hopefully cover everything you need to know to create your own games with Worldsmith Studio. If you feel something is missing, needs clarification, or you have a suggestion, please feel free to submit an issue . To view the latest version of this document online, please use this link .
0.title: Welcome

1.body: To get started, begin by learning about core concepts . If you want to get straight down to business, you can read about creating and opening projects. If you already have a project created that you want to build, see the section on building .
1.title: Getting Started

10.body: An asset store is like a directory. It contains 0 or more assets . Worldsmith defines several asset stores which are used for specific things in your world. You can read more about these in the asset stores section.
10.title: Asset Store

11.body: An asset is an encrypted file which you can use in your world. Assets are stored in asset stores . They can represent either a single file or a directory. Each asset is encrypted using Dart's encrypt package, and each one uses a randomly generated encryption key, so no two encryption keys are the same. Please note that while Worldsmith Studio does encrypt assets, no guarantees are given about the security of any assets you bundle with your world . The encryption keys for all assets are stored in plain text in your project file , and the encryption key for the encrypted world file is stored in plain text in the generated source code . As such, if you give either the project file, or the generated source code to another person, they will be able to decrypt your world and its assets. Worldsmith Studio attempts to mitigate this by generating a new encryption key and re-encrypting your world file every time you build your world, but you are fully responsible for any content created with the program.
11.title: Assets

12.body: When you run Worldsmith Studio for the first time, you will see a screen with buttons for creating and opening projects. A screenshot of Worldsmith Studio with no recently-opened projects. To create a project, you can click the "Create Project" button, or use the keyboard shortcut Control + N. You will see an appropriate dialogue for creating a file on your operating system. A screenshot showing a "Create Project" dialogue with a filename of project.json. It is recommended that you stick with the default filename project.json, but this is not enforced. Also, you can safely rename your project file any time it is not open in Worldsmith Studio. When you have selected a directory, and given your project a filename, you will be taken to the project settings for your new project. A screenshot showing Worldsmith Studio's project settings. The title of the world is "Untitled World". If you want to close your project and return to the main menu, you can click the back button, or press Control + W.
12.breadcrumbs: Creating A Project » Creating A Project
12.title: Creating A Project

13.body: When a project has been created, the main menu of Worldsmith Studio will change to show a list of recently-opened projects. The Worldsmith Studio main menu showing a recently-opened project with the path C:\Users\chris\src\RPG\project.json. It is worth noting that this list will only include files which still exist. If you move or rename a file before this list loads, it will not show up. You can click any of these files to open them, or choose a file from somewhere else by clicking the "Open Project" button or pressing Control + O.
13.breadcrumbs: Opening A Project » Opening A Project
13.title: Opening A Project

14.body: Worldsmith Studio has a lot of different screens. Every attempt has been made to ensure easy and consistent navigation across the different parts of the interface. If you find this not to be the case, please submit an issue .
14.breadcrumbs: Navigating The Interface » Navigating The Interface
14.title: Navigating The Interface

15.body: Many screens - most notably the main project screen - use tabs to provide an overview and context. You can navigate through these types of screens in several ways:
15.title: Tabbed Screens

16.body: You can click on the tabs at the bottom of the screen to move to a different tab. If you are using a keyboard, the left and right arrow keys also work to focus the different tabs, and the enter or space bar keys will select.
16.breadcrumbs: Navigating The Interface » Mouse Or Keyboard
16.title: Mouse Or Keyboard

17.body: You can use the key combination Control + Tab to navigate to the next tab, or Control + Shift + Tab to navigate to the previous one. This key combination will wrap around to the first tab when used in the last tab, and Control + Shift + Tab does the opposite.
17.title: Control + Tab

18.body: You can use the Control key in combination with the number row to move to the different tabs. For example, if you had three tabs, "First", "Seconds", and "Third", Control + 1 would move you to the "First" tab, Control + 2 to the "Second", and Control + 3 to the "Third". This works all the way up to Control + 9 for the ninth tab, and Control + 0 for the tenth.
18.title: Control + Numbers

19.body: When a number is displayed, such as when setting the frames per second for your world, you can use the equals (=) key to increase the number, and the dash (-) to decrease. How much these keys affect the value is dependant on the number being shown. For example, with frames per second, equals doubles the number, while dash halves it.
19.title: Numerical Controls

2.body: Worldsmith Studio is a fairly large program, and it will inevitably use terminology that is unfamiliar. To this end, this chapter attempts to introduce you to various concepts used by the program.
2.title: Concepts

20.body: If a set of coordinates is displayed, quite often you can use alt and the arrow keys to adjust the value. Alt + Up Arrow: Increase the y axis (move north). Alt + Right Arrow: Increase the x axis (move east). Alt + Down Arrow: Decrease the y axis (move south). Alt + Left Arrow: Decrease the x axis (move west).
20.title: Coordinates

21.body: When editing zones , you can move through the zone when you are focussed on the coordinates in the Canvas tab (Control + 2) by pressing control and the arrow keys. Control + Up Arrow: Move north. Control + Right Arrow: Move east. Control + Down Arrow: Move south. Control + Left Arrow: Move West.
21.title: Zone Movement

22.body: In many places, a searchable list is used. While typing in the search box, the number of search results will appear in brackets. The first control in the tab order after the search field is a "Clear" button, which will clear the search field, and return your focus to it. When moving through the search results, you can press the slash (/) key to return to the search field.
22.title: Searchable Lists

23.body: In places where a button will select from a list (commands, scenes, ETC), you can press Control + E to edit the selected item, rather than changing the selection.
23.title: Selection buttons

24.body: The world options screen allows you to configure basic settings for your project.
24.title: World Options

25.body: Commands in world smith studio can almost be compared to what it is in the reel world: Just like you can command someone to do something or give a command to a program, you can do the same in world smith studio. Commands are made up of a set of "instructions", which can affect your player and their world in different ways.
25.title: Commands

26.body: Set current zone: Used to set the current zone and / or coordinates for the player. Change walking mode: changes the walking mode of the player. Set quest stage: used to update quest progress. Call commands: calls any other created command. Custom event name: allows you to refer to any custom events in your dart code. Start conversation: Starts a conversation between the player and an NPC. Show scene: shows a created scene. Return to main menu: returns the player back to the main menu.
26.title: Available instructions

3.body: Computers use the words directory and folder interchangeably, to describe a section of your computer's filesystem where files and subdirectories or sub-folders are stored. Throughout this book, we will adopt the Mac OS X and *x terminology and use the word directory, despite Windows using the word Folder.
3.title: Directory

34.breadcrumbs: Appendix 1: Installing worldsmith » Appendix 1: Installing worldsmith
34.title: Appendix 1: Installing worldsmith

35.body: In order to either play or build your projects, you need the worldsmith command line tool. This is part of the worldsmith package.
35.title: Introduction

36.body: If you haven't already, ensure you have installed either Flutter , or Dart . Flutter is recommended. Next, make sure that the dart executable program is in your path. How to do this is beyond the scope of this manual. You should now be able to open up your console (for example cmd.exe on Windows, or Terminal on Linux or OS X), and type dart -v, and see output like the following: Dart SDK version: 2.16.1 (stable) (Tue Feb 8 12:02:33 2022 +0100) on "windows_x64"
36.title: Installing Dart

37.body: When all of this is done, you need to install the worldsmith package.
37.title: Installing Worldsmith

38.body: To install with dart pub (the Dart package manager), use the following command: dart pub global activate --overwrite worldsmith This will install the latest version of worldsmith from pub.dev . There may be changes that have not yet been included into this version, in particular beta testers of Worldsmith Studio will probably want to install from git .
38.breadcrumbs: Appendix 1: Installing worldsmith » Installing With Pub
38.title: Installing With Pub

39.body: To install from git, use the following command: dart pub global activate -s git --overwrite https://github.com/chrisnorman7/worldsmith Please be aware that there may be conflicts between the Git version of the worldsmith package, and the stable version of Worldsmith Studio.
39.breadcrumbs: Appendix 1: Installing worldsmith » Installing From Git
39.title: Installing From Git

4.body: Worldsmith Studio, as well as its accompanying package worldsmith are both written in Dart . This is a programming language created by Google. Any scripting of your game will also be done with Dart.
4.title: Dart

40.body: As a general rule, if you are beta testing Worldsmith Studio, install from git . If you are using the current stable release of Worldsmith Studio, use the version from pub .
40.breadcrumbs: Appendix 1: Installing worldsmith » Which Version Should I Choose?
40.title: Which Version Should I Choose?

41.body: It is possible to play through the projects you have created without building them. To do this, you need to use the worldsmith command line tool. If you haven't already got that installed, see the Installing Worldsmith section.
41.breadcrumbs: Appendix 2: Playing Projects » Appendix 2: Playing Projects
41.title: Appendix 2: Playing Projects

42.body: First, you'll need to know the directory where your worldsmith project has been created. Fir example, if your world file resides at C:\Users\chris\src\RPG\project.json, the directory you'll need is C:\Users\chris\src\RPG.
42.title: Getting Started

43.body: Begin by opening up your command prompt or terminal, and changing directories: cd project_directory Your prompt should change to alert you to the fact that your directory has changed.
43.title: Changing Directory

44.body: If this command does not work on Windows, try the pushd command instead: pushd project_directory You command prompt should now show the directory you just gave.
44.title: Windows Tip

45.body: If you used the default filename (project.json) during project creation , it should now be enough to type worldsmith play. If you chose a different filename, either rename the project file to project.json, or tell the worldsmith command what the filename is: worldsmith play -f game.json
45.breadcrumbs: Appendix 2: Playing Projects » Playing Your Game
45.title: Playing Your Game

46.body: To get more help from the program, type worldsmith play -h.
46.title: Getting Help

47.body: To build the projects, you will first need the worldsmith command line program. If you haven't already got that installed, see the Installing Worldsmith section. Building projects has only been tested under Windows. If you have problems with other operating systems, please submit an issue .
47.breadcrumbs: Appendix 3: Building Projects » Appendix 3: Building Projects
47.title: Appendix 3: Building Projects

48.body: The primary tools you need are Dart and worldsmith . If either of these aren't installed or on your path, please refer to the section on installing worldsmith .
48.title: Gather Tools

49.body:
By default, when building an EXE from a dart file under WIndows, a console window is opened when running the resulting EXE file. For a game, this is undesirable. The worldsmith build command gets around this by calling a program called editbin. If you want this to happen automatically, ensure editbin is installed and available on your path. According to this page , this is achieved by installing Visual Studio , and including the MSVC Command Line Toolset . In practise, Visual Studio's installer can be somewhat opaque, and it's worth installing more than you need to make sure you've got everything covered. Next, you need to make sure editbin is in your path. The quickest way to do that is to go into a Microsoft Visual Studio Command Prompt (which you can find in your start menu). Alternatively, modify your path, and include the path to the vcvars64.bat script. It will be located in a path like C:\Program Files\Microsoft Visual Studio\2022\Community\VC\Auxiliary\Build. Then you can just type vcvars64. You should see output like the following: **********************************************************************

5.body: A project refers to the overall directory on your computer where your world file and assets are stored. A project consists of a few things:
5.title: Project

50.body: Change to the directory where you project is stored. On most operating systems this is achieved with the cd command. cd c:\Users\chris\src\RPG This directory should have your asset stores directory, and your project's JSON file.
50.title: Change Directory

51.body: In order to run, the worldsmith command needs at least 2 libraries: synthizer SDL2 Optionally, if you are using assets that are neither in was or MP3 format: libsndfile should be included. You can find all of these libraries for your platform in the Worldsmith Studio directory.
51.title: Gather Libraries

6.body: This is a single file which is stored as JSON . It holds the information about your world. You can open this file in any standard text editor, although you are entirely responsible for any damage to your project arising from making edits to it outside of the official Worldsmith Studio editor.
6.title: Project File

7.body: This is the directory where your sound files will be encrypted and stored. It will contain sequentially numbered files and directories.
7.title: Assets Directory

8.body: If you have used the worldsmith build command, you will additionally have a game directory, where generated source code will reside. If you are running under Windows, this directory will also contain a .exe file which you can use to play your game without needing Dart installed.
8.title: Game Directory

9.body: A world is the game you are creating. This includes all zones , and commands .
9.title: World
